>>At one large institution, a rule was brought in that everyone had to change
>>their password every month, and every password had to contain alpha as well
>>as numeric characters.

	If I put on my "security hat" I'd have to make some statement
to the effect that with the advent of networking, the idea of passwords
became obsolete.

	Anyone who *cares* about security should use some kind of
token authentication scheme. There's really just no good argument
left for defending the continued use of passwords other than cost
and convenience.

mjr.
